{{Infobox football biography | name = Paulo Gazzaniga | image = Audi- quattro-Cup 09.JPG | image_size = 200 | caption = Gazzaniga playing for [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in 2015 | fullname = Paulo Dino Gazzaniga<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/465277 |title=Squads for 2017/18 Premier League confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=1 September 2017 |accessdate=9 September 2017}}</ref> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1992|1|2|df=y}}<ref name=Hugman>{{Hugman|23140|accessdate=23 August 2017}}</ref> | birth_place = [[Murphy, Santa Fe|Murphy]], Argentina | height = 1.96 m<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/4600/Paulo-Gazzaniga/overview |title=Paulo Gazzaniga: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=17 February 2018}}</ref> | position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]] | currentclub = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] | clubnumber = 22 | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = Unión y Cultura | youthyears2 = 2007–2011 | youthclubs2 = [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] | years1 = 2011–2012 | clubs1 = [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] | caps1 = 20 | goals1 = 0 | years2 = 2012–2017 | clubs2 = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] | caps2 = 21 | goals2 = 0 | years3 = 2016–2017 | clubs3 = → [[Rayo Vallecano]] (loan) | caps3 = 32 | goals3 = 0 | years4 = 2017– | clubs4 = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] | caps4 = 3 | goals4 = 0 | nationalyears1 = 2018– | nationalteam1 = [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] | nationalcaps1 = 1 | nationalgoals1 = 0 | club-update = 15:48, 27 November 2018 (UTC) | nationalteam-update = 15:48, 27 November 2018 (UTC) }} '''Paulo Dino Gazzaniga''' (born 2 January 1992) is an Argentine professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for {{English football updater|TottenhH}} club [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and the [[Argentina national football team|Argentina national team]].
==Early life== Gazzaniga was born in [[Murphy, Santa Fe]].<ref name=Hugman/>
==Club career== ===Early career=== Gazzaniga joined Spanish club [[Valencia CF|Valencia]]'s youth setup in 2007,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.plazadeportiva.com/ver/2676/los-porteros-suplentes-que-el-valencia-dejo-escapar.html |title=Los porteros "suplentes" que el Valencia dejó escapar|trans-title=The "reserve" goalkeepers who Valencia let out |publisher=Plaza Deportiva |language=Spanish |date=26 January 2013 |accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref> after starting out with hometown side Unión y Cultura.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.goal.com/es-ar/news/4442/argentinos-por-el-mundo/2012/09/22/3393889/paulo-gazzaniga-debut-argentino-en-la-premier-league |title=Paulo Gazzaniga, debut argentino en la Premier League|trans-title=Paulo Gazzaniga, Argentine debut in Premier League |publisher=Goal.com |language=Spanish |date=22 September 2012 |accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref> However, he failed to make a first team appearance for ''Los Che'', and was subsequently released in May 2011.{{cn|date=September 2018}}
In July 2011, Gazzaniga signed a two-year contract with [[EFL League Two|League Two]] club [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]], to challenge [[Ross Flitney]] for the number one spot.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.herefordunited.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10835~2481771,00.html |title=Gillingham sign goalkeeper Paulo Gazzaniga |publisher=Hereford United F.C. |date=28 July 2011 |accessdate=23 October 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111018083904/http://www.herefordunited.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10835~2481771%2C00.html |archivedate=18 October 2011 |df=}}</ref> Gazzaniga was recommended to Gillingham manager [[Andy Hessenthaler]] by [[Gary Penrice]], [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]]'s European scout, following his release from Valencia.<ref>{{Cite book |title=The Nowhere Men: The Unknown Story of Football's True Talent Spotters |last=Calvin |first=Michael |publisher=Random House |year=2014 |isbn=9780099580263 |location= |pages=166}}</ref> He made his professional debut for the club on 4 October, in a 3–1 home defeat to [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] in the [[EFL Trophy|Football League Trophy]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15071257.stm |title=Gillingham 1–3 Barnet |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 October 2011 |accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref>
===Southampton=== On 20 July 2012, Gazzaniga signed a four-year deal with newly promoted [[Premier League]] side [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]], with [[Tommy Forecast]] going to Gillingham on loan as part of the deal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18921908 |title=Southampton sign Gillingham goalkeeper Paulo Gazzaniga |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=20 July 2012 |date=20 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Saint Paulo Becomes Fourth Signing |url=http://www.saintsfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10280~2854836,00.html |publisher=Southampton F.C. |accessdate=20 July 2012 |date=20 July 2012}}</ref> He described it as "a crazy situation" but said it was like "a dream".<ref>{{cite news |title=Saints summer spending continues as Gazzaniga checks in from Gillingham |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2176401/Southampton-sign-Paulo-Gazzaniga.html |newspaper=Daily Mail |location=London |accessdate=20 July 2012 |date=20 July 2012}}{{Unreliable source?|date=August 2017}}</ref>
Gazzaniga made his debut on 28 August in a 4–1 victory against [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]] in the second round of the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Stevenage 1–4 Southampton |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19340365 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=24 September 2014 |date=28 August 2012}}</ref> He made his league debut almost a month later, on 22 September in a 4–1 win against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lewis |first1=Aimee |title=Southampton 4–1 Aston Villa |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19615244 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=24 September 2014 |date=22 September 2012}}</ref>
Gazzaniga was used as cover for first choice keepers [[Kelvin Davis (footballer)|Kelvin Davis]], [[Artur Boruc]] and [[Fraser Forster]], making only two appearances in [[2014–15 Southampton F.C. season|2014–15]].<ref name=sb1415/>
He made two Premier League appearances in the [[2015–16 Southampton F.C. season|2015–16]] season, in the 1–0 defeat away to [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] and a home 2–0 defeat to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], both in December 2015.<ref>{{cite news |title=Crystal Palace 1 Southampton 0 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/35014153 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=13 December 2015 |date=12 December 2015}}</ref> He signed a new four-year deal with Southampton on 11 September 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.saintsfc.co.uk/news/article/20150911-paulo-gazzaniga-contract-2019-2682477.aspx |title=Paulo Gazzaniga extends contract until 2019 |publisher=Southampton F.C. |date=11 September 2015 |access-date=22 June 2016}}</ref>
On 29 July 2016, Gazzaniga joined [[Segunda División]] club [[Rayo Vallecano]] on loan for the [[2016–17 Rayo Vallecano season|2016–17 season]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Gazzaniga joins Rayo on season-long loan |url=http://www.saintsfc.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/20160729-paulo-gazzaniga-southampton-rayo-vallecano-loan-3213584.aspx |publisher=Southampton F.C. |date=29 July 2016 |accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref>
===Tottenham Hotspur=== On 23 August 2017, Gazzaniga signed for fellow Premier League club [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] on a five-year contract. He reunited with his compatriot and former Southampton manager, [[Mauricio Pochettino]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Tottenham sign Southampton goalkeeper Paulo Gazzaniga |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41026072 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=23 August 2017 |accessdate=23 August 2017}}</ref> He made his Premier League debut for the club on 5 November 2017, playing in a 1–0 victory against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Son Heung-Min strikes as Tottenham squeeze past Crystal Palace |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/report?gameId=480800 |publisher=ESPN Sport |date=5 November 2017 |accessdate=5 November 2017}}</ref> Pochettino said that Gazzaniga performed "fantastically well" on his debut.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hafez |first1=Shamoon |title=Tottenham Hotspur 1 Crystal Palace 0 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41792810 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=5 November 2017 |date=5 November 2017}}</ref>
In [[2018–19 Tottenham Hotspur F.C. season|2018–19]] after starting for Tottenham in the [[Premier League]] against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] and [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]], in the [[EFL Cup]] against [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] and in the [[2018–19 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] home fixture against [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]], he earned his first [[Argentina national football team|Argentina national team]] call-up.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2018/november/argentina-call-for-gazzaniga/ |title=Argentina call for Gazzaniga |work=Tottenham Hotspur F.C. |date=9 November 2018 |accessdate=10 November 2018}}</ref>
==International career== Gazzaniga made his first international appearance on 20 November 2018, coming off the bench to replace [[Gerónimo Rulli]] in the 59th minute in a friendly match against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], and helped keep a clean sheet in a 2–0 win for Argentina.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=527646 |title=Argentina knocks off Mexico with Mauro Icardi, Paulo Dybala goals |website=espn.com |date=21 November 2018 |accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref>
